    "desc": "Scientific computation language.",
    "long_intro": "Fortran (Formula Translation) is a high-level programming language for scientific computing.\n        It was the first widely used high-level language and remains a giant in its field.\n        Fortran is specifically designed for numerical and high-performance computation.\n        The language is a cornerstone of weather forecasting and climate change modeling.\n        It features native support for complex numbers and high-precision arithmetic.\n        Fortran's array-handling capabilities are unmatched for large-scale simulations.\n        The language is essential for high-end aerospace and nuclear engineering research.\n        Many of the world's fastest supercomputers spend their time running Fortran code.\n        It is known for its extreme efficiency and ability to handle massive data arrays.\n        Fortran has evolved over decades, with modern standards like Fortran 2018.\n        The language integrates with modern tools through libraries like OpenMP and MPI.\n        It is essential for developing high-performance solvers for CFD and FEA software.\n        Fortran remains the most trusted language for mission-critical scientific tasks.\n        The platform's compilers are highly optimized for speed on all modern processors.\n        It provides a stable and reliable foundation for long-term engineering projects.\n        Fortran is a core part of the legacy and future of high-performance computing (HPC).\n        The language's simplicity in mathematical notation is a major benefit for scientists.\n        Mastering Fortran is essential for careers in supercomputing and numerical R&D.\n        It continues to be a vital tool for solving the most challenging math problems.\n        Fortran's legacy of performance ensures it will remain relevant for decades more.",
    "long_benefits": "1. Unmatched performance in large-scale numerical and scientific computing.\n        2. Native support for complex numbers and multi-dimensional array math.\n        3. Highly optimized compilers for maximum speed on modern CPU architectures.\n        4. Industry-standard for weather forecasting and global climate simulations.\n        5. Essential for high-performance CFD, FEA, and nuclear physics research.\n        6. Mature and stable language with decades of verified scientific libraries.\n        7. Native support for parallel programming via Coarrays and OpenMP/MPI.\n        8. Extreme efficiency in handling massive datasets and high-precision math.\n        9. Evolution into modern standards like Fortran 2008 and Fortran 2018.\n        10. Foundation of the world's most powerful supercomputing applications.\n        11. Simple and direct mathematical notation for scientists and engineers.\n        12. Long-term reliability and compatibility for multi-decade research projects.\n        13. Status as the \"gold standard\" for numerical speed and reliability.\n        14. Deeply integrated with specialized scientific libraries (LAPACK, BLAS).\n        15. Minimal overhead compared to modern high-level dynamic languages.\n        16. Proven success in mission-critical aerospace and defense simulations.\n        17. Essential skill for careers in high-end supercomputing centers (HPC).\n        18. Reliable performance on both legacy and next-generation computer systems.\n        19. Global community of experts and researchers maintaining core libraries.\n        20. Longevity that ensures your scientific code remains valid for years."
